title: For Sale/Trade:  Walther H&k HK 416 D .22lr HV Tactical AR Style Carbine Umarex Trade For MPA Masterpiece 9mm Pistol Or?
postcontent:
Wife bought this for me on Valentines day last year for about $640 from big 5. Nothing says love like a deadly weapon. Took it camping a few times and have fired exactly 60 rounds through it. Quality product so as expected it had no issues. 

 Came with the 10 round magazine and we bought an additional 20. Comes with everything shown in the photos. Rifle in original box, 1-10 round and 1-20 round magazine. the original stupid cable lock still in its bag. I can't seem to find the manual for it but it is available online. 

 Rifle has been in and out of the safe a few times and out in the woods. Has some small handling marks on it. Most noticeable is a light paint scratch on the top of the barrel as seen in the photo. 

 I looked at some of the ar style .22 rifles and have to say this one was in my opinion the best. The weight is substantial. Hold this in one hand and the Mossberg or Colt version in the other and you will see what I mean. This is metal and solid. A great trainer.

 I am looking to trade this more than sell it. I have specific trade desires and am not in a hurry to get rid of this .22. Original receipt in hand shows 649.99 on sale from 750. Too much I know but I really liked it. Now I want a Masterpiece Arms M10 or M11 pistol in 9mm. Would like one with its factory accessories and case if possible but am flexible.

 Would meet face to face anywhere between Lynnwood and Arlington Have a preprinted Bill of sale we can fill out for each of our records.

 From Manufacturer:
 The .22 caliber HK 416 is loaded with authentic features. From its appearance, feel, and operation, right down to the sling swivel incorporated into the stock, the 416 D145RS is a replica in every sense.

 Like all the .22 LR H&K's, the 416 is a dedicated .22 rimfire rifle. It is engineered and built in Germany by Carl Walther with a match grade precision barrel, upper and lower metal receivers, a retractable stock, and a machined rail interface system. The 416’s pistol grip and buttstock are authentic in that they include storage compartments for small tools or batteries.

 The magazines for the .22 caliber 416 are made of high-strength polymer and are designed to make loading simple and efficient. They’re available in either a 20- or 10-round version. 

 The .22 caliber HK 416 D145RS operates on a blowback system. The dust cover functions and the bolt holds open when the magazine empties. Its sights are on-rail and the rear sight is adjustable for windage and elevation. Its safety selector rotates 90 degrees from ‘On Safe’ to ‘Fire’. Take down for basic cleaning is simple—there are no loose parts. Just remove the rear receiver pin and pivot the upper receiver to open.

title: For Sale:  GUN SHOW AND TELL BEAVERTON,OREGON
postcontent:
Frontline Arms  Is Proud to Present
  First Thursday GUN SHOW & TELL
At Our NEW Location 
Across the Street From the Beaverton Post Office  



What:    Gun Show and Tell 
When:   First Thursday February 6th, 6:30pm to 9:00pm 
Where:   Frontline Arms
             12150 SW 1st ST,
           Beaverton, OR 97005


  Gun Show & Tell is this week Thursday the 6th. Come and help us put a new twist on an old tradition… SHOW AND TELL. Remember showing of your cool stuff to classmates? Same idea except now you'll be presenting your favorite guns to other firearms enthusiasts. Beside seeing all the cool guns and meeting new friends, enjoy some free food and a soft drink on us.  

SHOW US WHAT YOU'VE GOT!

  Of course we can't do it without your help. So I'm writing to those of you who have unique guns or stories you'd like to share with your fellow firearms fans. When it's your turn, bring your firearm to the table at the front of the room and tell it's special story. We are asking that you only bring one or two guns so that everyone will have time to present their pieces to the group. Of course you don't have to bring a gun to join in. Just bring your interest in firearms and your desire to meet other firearms enthusiasts.

  EXERCISE YOUR RIGHTS…SAFELY  

We encourage and welcome anyone concealed or open carrying as long as you have a current CHL recognized by Oregon. However for everyones safety we REQUIRE your co-operation by NOT having any of your show and tell weapons loaded. Also before you hand any firearm to someone (even your concealed or open carry gun) unload it in a safe direction, no loaded magazines, no round in the chamber.

  TAKE A LOAD OFF, RELAX  

For your convenience you are welcome to have your firearms placed on the gun wall behind the counter, in your view, until it is your turn to present them or you would like to show them to someone. Just ask and we will be glad to ta! ke them off the wall for you. This way you can have your hands free to eat or just relax knowing your firearms are always safe behind the counter and always in your sight.  

SMILE FOR THE CAMERA

  In order to promote Frontline Arms and the Gun Show and Tell we will be taking photos and video at the event. By attending the event you are giving your consent for your likeness as well as the likeness of any of your firearms or show and tell items to be used by Frontline Arms for promotional purposes. If you do not want your likeness used please let John or Casey know and we will not include you or your firearms in our promotions.  

HELP US MAKE FRONTLINE ARMS GUN SHOW AND TELL THE EVENT FOR EVERY FIRST THURSDAY  

Obviously we need to make a profit to stay in business and provide these events for the community. Also by ATF's definition this event IS a GUN SHOW. As a gun show the law requires that the proper forms be filled out and that the buyer pass a background check before the firearm may be transferred. In exchange for creating a marketplace and assisting in the sale Frontline Arms will charge the seller $25 per firearm sold and the buyer $10 to perform a background check ( the $10 goes to OSP). Just to be clear, we don't expect you to sale your gun if you show it, just letting you know the option is there if you want to.

 We look forward to seeing you Thursday February 6th, at 6:30PM  

Thank You, 
John Laird, Owner --&-- Casey Dean  CEO/MANAGER

postcontent:
As the title says, if you have a preban norinco or polytech AK, chances are I want it. 

I am willing to pay anywhere from $1,000 to about $2,000 depending on the model and condition. I pay more for under folders and I pay more for polytechs. I actually prefer 56s though. I am only looking for pre bans and I do not want guns that are in horrible condition. Either way, if it's Chinese, I probably want it!

Here is a very rough scale of what I am looking to pay based on condition and model:

*NIB or LNIB Polytech: 1.5k-2k, depending on condition and model. 
*Used but in good condition polytech: 1.2-1.5k depending on condition and model.

*NIB or LNIB 56s: 1.3-1.5 depeding on condition and model.
*Used but in good condition 56s: 1k-1.3k depending on condition and model.

I know what these guns are worth. If you are only willing to sell if someone offers you an absurd amount, then please do not contact me. 

There's plenty other fish to catch, just not here.

title: For Trade:  Answer to Offers
postcontent: For the idiot who doesn't know... When you list something for trade only it doesn't give you an option for a price. Therefore the user lists what he has and what he's interested in and hopes for a reply.  If you don't know what you it's worth that's not their fault. If you do and you have what they want and there's a value difference you negotiate. Thus the "FUN" in trading. If you don't know how to play the game get out while your behind. title: For Sale:  9mm Tokarev Customized to shoot
location: Santa Fe, NM, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
This is one of my shooters, and is set up as such. It has a very nice action and a crisp trigger. I have converted the sights to three-dot type, using orange fluorescent paint in dimples on the rear. This can be taken off with a little nail polish remover if you don't like them, or changed to a different color. Front sight is not dimpled since I didn't want to do anything to it to permanently modify it. You may notice an unusual set of grips on it. The originals will come with it, but what is on it now is a modified set of Colt Commander aftermarket grips. These are EXTREMELY comfortable and thinner and more sticky than the factory grips. They are secured with Allen screws and are attractive. I would recommend shooting it with these grips on it before you swap back to the Chinese Tok grips. If you do, I doubt you will want to swap them back. It is a shooter, and not really a collectible pistol anyway. But you'll get the original grips just in case. It also has heat-fitted grip tape on the grip frame front and rear. This again makes the grip sticky. Done like this, I prefer shooting my Toks over almost any other of my 9mms. Just pull it off if you don't like it.

 This pistol has been used as a range gun by me, as just a plinker. I also kept it by my bed for a couple of years. That is how reliable I believe it to be. 

 The days of cheap 7.62x25 ammo are apparently long gone, so it is cool to have one of these 9mms around so you can afford to actually shoot it. They are great guns in 9mm, and this one has NEVER had a FTF or FTE or any other kind of malfunction. Unfortunately, I only have one magazine for it. I bought it without a box, so that is long gone as well.

I am firm on my price on this. They go for more online and you would have to pay shipping, sales tax, and a dealer fee to get one. And even then you would not have the grip mod or the sights. Plus I KNOW this one is reliable!

Thanks for reading my very long ad as usual. 

 Doby Pilgrim
 Santa Fe, NM
